{
 "level": "B1–B2",
 "intro": "In this topic, you will see when to choose <strong>Future Continuous</strong> and when to choose <strong>Future Perfect</strong>: are we asking <strong>what will be happening then</strong> or <strong>what will already be finished by that point</strong>?",
 "rules": [
  {
   "label": "FUTURE CONTINUOUS",
   "color": "amber",
   "text": "<strong>will be + V-ing</strong> for an action that will be <strong>in progress</strong> at a future moment.",
   "example": "At 8 p.m. tomorrow, I'll be working. / This time tomorrow, she'll be flying."
  },
  {
   "label": "FUTURE PERFECT",
   "color": "violet",
   "text": "<strong>will have + V3</strong> for an action that will <strong>already be complete</strong> by a future limit or deadline.",
   "example": "By 8 p.m., I'll have finished the report. / By then, they'll have arrived."
  },
  {
   "label": "KEY QUESTION",
   "color": "blue",
   "text": "Ask yourself: <strong>what will be happening then?</strong> or <strong>what will already be finished by then?</strong>",
   "example": "future process at that point / completed result before that point"
  }
 ]
}

{
 "title": "1. Quick comparison",
 "intro": "Both forms look to the future, but the focus is different:",
 "rows": [
  {
   "en": "Future Continuous",
   "ua": "an action in progress at a future point",
   "note": "At 8 p.m. tomorrow, I'll be driving home."
  },
  {
   "en": "Future Perfect",
   "ua": "a completed result by a future limit",
   "note": "By 8 p.m., I'll have finished the report."
  },
  {
   "en": "this time tomorrow / at 8 p.m. tomorrow",
   "ua": "we ask what will be happening then",
   "note": "This time tomorrow, she'll be taking the exam."
  },
  {
   "en": "by 8 p.m. / by then / by the time",
   "ua": "we ask what will already be done by that point",
   "note": "By the time you arrive, we'll have eaten."
  },
  {
   "en": "process vs result",
   "ua": "ongoing action vs completed result",
   "note": "will be working vs will have finished"
  }
 ],
 "warning": "If it matters that the action will still be happening then, choose <strong>Future Continuous</strong>. If it matters that the result will already be ready by the limit, choose <strong>Future Perfect</strong>."
}

{
 "title": "2. Forms grid",
 "intro": "Compare the basic affirmative, negative, and question patterns.",
 "items": [
  {
   "label": "Future Continuous",
   "title": "Affirmative",
   "subtitle": "Subject + will be + V-ing: I will be working."
  },
  {
   "label": "Future Continuous",
   "title": "Negative",
   "subtitle": "Subject + won't be + V-ing: I won't be working."
  },
  {
   "label": "Future Continuous",
   "title": "Question",
   "subtitle": "Will + subject + be + V-ing? Will you be working at 8 p.m.?"
  },
  {
   "label": "Future Perfect",
   "title": "Affirmative",
   "subtitle": "Subject + will have + V3: I will have finished."
  },
  {
   "label": "Future Perfect",
   "title": "Negative",
   "subtitle": "Subject + won't have + V3: I won't have finished."
  },
  {
   "label": "Future Perfect",
   "title": "Question",
   "subtitle": "Will + subject + have + V3? Will you have finished by 8 p.m.?"
  }
 ]
}

{
 "title": "3. When the meaning changes",
 "sections": [
  {
   "label": "A future point",
   "color": "amber",
   "description": "Choose <strong>Future Continuous</strong> when you want to show an action <strong>in progress</strong> at a specific future moment.",
   "examples": [
    {
     "en": "At 8 p.m. tomorrow, I'll be driving home.",
     "ua": "The action will still be in progress at that moment."
    },
    {
     "en": "This time tomorrow, they'll be taking the exam.",
     "ua": "The focus is on what will be happening then."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "label": "A deadline or limit",
   "color": "violet",
   "description": "Choose <strong>Future Perfect</strong> when it matters that the action <strong>will already be complete</strong> before another future point.",
   "examples": [
    {
     "en": "By 8 p.m., I'll have finished the report.",
     "ua": "The result will already be ready by then."
    },
    {
     "en": "By the time you call, she'll have left.",
     "ua": "One action will finish before the other future event."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "label": "A paired contrast",
   "color": "blue",
   "description": "The context is similar, but the focus changes: a process at a point or a completed result by a limit.",
   "examples": [
    {
     "en": "At 8 p.m., we'll be eating dinner.",
     "ua": "We ask what will be happening then."
    },
    {
     "en": "By 8 p.m., we'll have eaten dinner.",
     "ua": "We ask what will already be finished by then."
    }
   ],
   "note": "<strong>at this time / at 8 p.m.</strong> often points to <strong>Future Continuous</strong>, while <strong>by then / by the time / by 8 p.m.</strong> often points to <strong>Future Perfect</strong>."
  }
 ]
}

{
 "title": "4. Typical mistakes",
 "items": [
  {
   "label": "Mistake 1",
   "color": "amber",
   "title": "Using Future Perfect when the action will still be in progress at that moment",
   "wrong": "❌ At 8 p.m. tomorrow, I will have worked on the report.",
   "right": "✅ At 8 p.m. tomorrow, I will be working on the report."
  },
  {
   "label": "Mistake 2",
   "color": "violet",
   "title": "Using Future Continuous when a finished result is needed by a deadline",
   "wrong": "❌ By 8 p.m., I will be finishing the report.",
   "right": "✅ By 8 p.m., I will have finished the report."
  },
  {
   "label": "Mistake 3",
   "color": "blue",
   "title": "Mixing up the time markers",
   "wrong": "❌ By the time you arrive, we will be finish dinner.",
   "right": "✅ By the time you arrive, we will have finished dinner."
  },
  {
   "label": "Mistake 4",
   "color": "rose",
   "title": "Breaking the form",
   "wrong": "❌ will be finish / will have finishing",
   "right": "✅ will be + V-ing / will have + V3"
  }
 ]
}

{
 "title": "5. A short decision guide",
 "items": [
  "Do you need to show that the action <strong>will be in progress at a future moment</strong>? → choose <strong>Future Continuous</strong>.",
  "Do you need to show that the action <strong>will already be complete by a deadline</strong>? → choose <strong>Future Perfect</strong>.",
  "Markers like <strong>at 8 p.m. tomorrow</strong> or <strong>this time tomorrow</strong> often point to <strong>will be + V-ing</strong>.",
  "Markers like <strong>by 8 p.m.</strong>, <strong>by then</strong>, or <strong>by the time</strong> often point to <strong>will have + V3</strong>.",
  "If you are unsure, ask out loud: <strong>what will be happening then?</strong> or <strong>what will already be finished by then?</strong>"
 ]
}

